---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ToolPageCta from '../../components/ToolPageCta.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';
import AdUnit from '../../components/AdUnit.astro';

const faq = [
  {
    question: "Why is cloud egress so expensive compared to ingress?",
    answer: "Cloud providers charge for data leaving their network (egress) because it represents a real cost — they pay for transit bandwidth to internet exchanges and peering partners. Ingress (data entering the cloud) is almost always free because it encourages data lock-in. Egress pricing creates a significant switching cost: once you store petabytes in one cloud, moving it out becomes expensive. This is a deliberate pricing strategy, not just infrastructure cost recovery."
  },
  {
    question: "What is the cheapest cloud provider for egress costs?",
    answer: "Google Cloud is generally the cheapest for internet egress among the major three, with rates starting at $0.085/GB for the first 10 TB/month (lower than AWS's $0.09/GB and Azure's $0.087/GB). However, for inter-region transfer within the same cloud, the comparison varies by route. Cloudflare R2 eliminates egress fees entirely (free egress to the internet), making it the cheapest option for object storage egress if it meets your use case."
  },
  {
    question: "How does using a CDN reduce egress costs?",
    answer: "CDN providers like CloudFront (AWS), Azure CDN, and Cloud CDN (GCP) have deeply discounted egress rates compared to direct-from-origin egress. CloudFront charges $0.0085–$0.012/GB vs S3's $0.09/GB for US regions — roughly 10x cheaper for content delivery. CDNs also cache content at edge locations, reducing origin fetches and thereby reducing the total volume of origin egress charged. For high-traffic public content, a CDN can reduce egress bills by 80–95%."
  },
  {
    question: "What is the free egress tier on AWS, GCP, and Azure?",
    answer: "AWS provides 100 GB/month free egress to the internet. GCP provides 200 GB/month free egress to the internet. Azure provides 5 GB/month free egress (via the free tier). Additionally, all three providers offer free inbound data transfer. For development, testing, and low-traffic applications, these free tiers can cover egress costs entirely. AWS also offers 1 TB/month free CloudFront egress via its free tier, which is significantly more useful for content delivery."
  },
  {
    question: "How much does inter-region data transfer cost on AWS vs GCP vs Azure?",
    answer: "Inter-region transfer costs vary significantly. On AWS, sending data between US regions costs $0.02/GB; between US and EU costs $0.02/GB; between US and Asia costs $0.08/GB. On GCP, same-continent transfer costs $0.01/GB; cross-continent costs $0.08/GB. Azure charges $0.02/GB for intra-continent (Zone 1) and $0.05–$0.08/GB for cross-continent transfers. GCP is cheapest for same-continent transfers; AWS and Azure are comparable for cross-continent."
  },
  {
    question: "What is the best strategy to minimize cloud egress costs for a multi-region application?",
    answer: "The most effective strategies are: (1) Keep compute and storage in the same region to avoid inter-region transfer fees. (2) Use CDNs for all user-facing content — CDN egress rates are 5–10x cheaper than origin egress. (3) Compress data before transfer — gzip/brotli can reduce transfer volume by 60–80% for text content. (4) Use PrivateLink/Private Service Connect to keep traffic on the provider's backbone rather than the public internet. (5) Consider Cloudflare R2 for egress-free object storage, fronted by Cloudflare CDN."
  }
];
---
<BaseLayout
  title="Cloud Egress Cost Calculator — Multi-Cloud Egress Cost Comparison"
  description="Comprehensive guide to cloud egress pricing across AWS, GCP, and Azure. Compare egress tiers, inter-region transfer costs, CDN vs direct rates, free tier allocations, and strategies to reduce your egress bill."
  tool="cloud-egress-cost-calculator"
  faq={faq}
>
  <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-2">Cloud Egress Cost Calculator</h1>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-6">Compare egress pricing across AWS, GCP, and Azure — internet egress, inter-region transfer, CDN rates, and practical strategies to cut your data transfer bill.</p>

  <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6 text-sm text-text-muted flex-wrap">
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> AWS vs GCP vs Azure egress rates</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Inter-region transfer pricing</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> CDN vs direct-origin comparison</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Cost reduction strategies</span>
  </div>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">Understanding Cloud Egress Pricing</h2>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">
    Egress costs — charges for data leaving a cloud provider's network — are one of the most misunderstood and frequently underestimated components of cloud bills. Unlike compute or storage costs that scale predictably with usage, egress costs can spike dramatically as applications grow, and they create significant friction when attempting to migrate or distribute workloads across providers.
  </p>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">
    The three major cloud providers (AWS, GCP, Azure) all follow a tiered pricing model for internet egress: the first tier is priced highest, with rates declining for higher monthly volumes. However, even the lowest tiers remain substantially higher than the actual cost of bandwidth, as egress pricing is also a customer retention mechanism.
  </p>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-6">
    Understanding the different egress categories is essential: <strong>Internet egress</strong> (cloud to the public internet), <strong>inter-region transfer</strong> (between regions within the same cloud), <strong>inter-zone transfer</strong> (between availability zones in the same region), and <strong>CDN egress</strong> (via the provider's content delivery network). Each has different rates, and optimizing where you fall in each category can dramatically reduce costs.
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">Internet Egress Rate Comparison — AWS vs GCP vs Azure</h2>
  <table class="w-full text-sm text-text-muted mb-6 border-collapse">
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th class="text-left border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 pb-2 pr-4">Monthly Volume</th>
        <th class="text-left border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 pb-2 pr-4">AWS ($/GB)</th>
        <th class="text-left border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 pb-2 pr-4">GCP ($/GB)</th>
        <th class="text-left border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 pb-2 pr-4">Azure ($/GB)</th>
        <th class="text-left border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 pb-2 pr-4">Free Tier</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">0–100 GB / 0–1 TB</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.09 (after 100 GB free)</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.085 (after 200 GB free)</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.087 (after 5 GB free)</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">AWS 100 GB / GCP 200 GB / Azure 5 GB</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">1–10 TB / 10 TB</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.09</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.085</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.083</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">—</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">10–50 TB / 10–50 TB</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.085</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.065</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.07</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">—</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">50–150 TB / 50+ TB</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.07</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.045</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.05</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">—</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">150+ TB</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.05</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.045</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.05</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">Contact for custom pricing</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p class="text-text-muted text-xs mb-6">Rates shown are for US/EU regions (Zone 1). Asia-Pacific and South America regions are typically 30–50% higher. Prices are approximate — always verify at each provider's pricing page.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">Inter-Region Transfer Costs</h2>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">
    Inter-region transfers — data moving between two regions within the same cloud — are a common hidden cost in multi-region architectures. Read replicas, cross-region replication, and active-active deployments all generate inter-region traffic that can add up quickly at scale.
  </p>
  <table class="w-full text-sm text-text-muted mb-6 border-collapse">
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th class="text-left border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 pb-2 pr-4">Route</th>
        <th class="text-left border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 pb-2 pr-4">AWS ($/GB)</th>
        <th class="text-left border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 pb-2 pr-4">GCP ($/GB)</th>
        <th class="text-left border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 pb-2 pr-4">Azure ($/GB)</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">Same continent (e.g., US East ↔ US West)</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.02</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.01</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.02</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">US ↔ Europe</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.02</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.08</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.05</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">US ↔ Asia Pacific</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.08</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.08</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.08</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">Same region, cross-AZ</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.01 each way</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.01 each way</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">Free</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">Same region, same AZ</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">Free (private IP)</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">Free</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">Free</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">CDN Egress vs Direct Egress</h2>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">
    For user-facing content, using the cloud provider's CDN reduces egress costs dramatically. CDN pricing leverages the provider's bulk bandwidth agreements with internet exchanges, passing savings to customers. The trade-off is that CDN pricing applies to edge-to-user delivery, not all traffic patterns — API calls, database queries, and server-to-server communication cannot be served from CDN.
  </p>
  <table class="w-full text-sm text-text-muted mb-6 border-collapse">
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th class="text-left border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 pb-2 pr-4">Provider</th>
        <th class="text-left border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 pb-2 pr-4">Direct Egress ($/GB)</th>
        <th class="text-left border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 pb-2 pr-4">CDN Egress ($/GB)</th>
        <th class="text-left border-b border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 pb-2 pr-4">CDN Savings</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">AWS (S3 → CloudFront)</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.09</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.0085–$0.012</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">~87–91%</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">GCP (GCS → Cloud CDN)</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.085</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.02–$0.04</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">~53–76%</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">Azure (Blob → Azure CDN)</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.087</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.0075–$0.015</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">~83–91%</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">Cloudflare R2 + CDN</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.00 (free egress)</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">$0.00</td>
        <td class="py-2 pr-4 border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800">100%</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p class="text-text-muted text-xs mb-6">CDN rates shown are for US/EU regions, first 10 TB tier. Origin-to-CDN transfer is typically free within the same provider. Cloudflare R2 is an S3-compatible object store with zero egress fees.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">Strategies to Reduce Egress Costs</h2>
  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 text-text-muted mb-4 space-y-2">
    <li><strong>Co-locate compute and storage:</strong> The single most impactful optimization. Keep your application servers and databases in the same region. Cross-region reads from a database can silently generate large inter-region bills at $0.02–$0.08/GB.</li>
    <li><strong>Use CDN for all public content:</strong> Images, videos, static assets, and downloadable files should always go through a CDN. CloudFront and Azure CDN offer the best rates at high volumes. Consider Cloudflare (external CDN) as a zero-egress alternative — traffic from origin to Cloudflare is free for AWS if you use Cloudflare's Bandwidth Alliance partnerships.</li>
    <li><strong>Enable compression:</strong> Gzip or Brotli compression on HTTP responses can reduce text-based transfer volume by 60–80%. This reduces both billable egress and improves end-user latency. Enable at the web server level (nginx, Apache) or CDN level for maximum coverage.</li>
    <li><strong>Use PrivateLink / Private Service Connect:</strong> AWS PrivateLink and GCP Private Service Connect let you access services over the provider's backbone rather than the public internet, often at lower rates and without internet egress charges. Particularly valuable for high-volume service-to-service communication.</li>
    <li><strong>Same-AZ communication:</strong> In AWS, traffic between EC2 instances in the same Availability Zone using private IPs is free. Explicitly placing related services in the same AZ (with redundancy in a second AZ) can eliminate cross-AZ charges for hot paths.</li>
    <li><strong>Consider Cloudflare R2 for object storage:</strong> R2 is S3-compatible, costs $0.015/GB/month for storage, and has zero egress fees to the internet via Cloudflare's CDN. For applications with high read traffic on stored objects (images, files), this can be dramatically cheaper than S3 + CloudFront at scale.</li>
    <li><strong>Audit and right-size logging and monitoring:</strong> Verbose logs, metrics, and traces sent across regions or to external SIEMs can generate surprising egress. Consider filtering at source, using provider-native monitoring, or using agents that batch and compress before sending.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-4">Egress Cost Examples at Scale</h2>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">
    To illustrate how egress costs accumulate, consider a media platform streaming 100 TB/month of video to end users from AWS S3 in us-east-1:
  </p>
  <ul class="list-disc pl-6 text-text-muted mb-6 space-y-2">
    <li><strong>Direct S3 egress (no CDN):</strong> First 1 TB at $0.09 = $92 + remaining 99 TB at $0.085–$0.07 = ~$7,600/month. Total: ~$7,700/month.</li>
    <li><strong>Via CloudFront CDN:</strong> 100 TB at ~$0.008/GB = ~$800/month. Savings: ~$6,900/month (90% reduction).</li>
    <li><strong>Via Cloudflare R2 + CDN:</strong> Storage cost (~$1,500/month for 100 TB stored) + $0 egress. Total: ~$1,500/month for storage only. Significant savings if read-to-write ratio is high.</li>
  </ul>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-6">
    At this scale, the CDN alone saves over $80,000 per year compared to direct egress. For any application serving significant user-facing content, CDN adoption is the highest-ROI optimization available.
  </p>

  <AdUnit slot="auto" format="auto" label="Advertisement" />
  <FaqSection faq={faq} />
  <ToolPageCta currentTool="cloud-egress-cost-calculator" relatedTags={['aws', 'gcp', 'azure', 'cloud', 'egress', 'cost-optimization', 'networking']} />
</BaseLayout>
